rights to citizenship. If racism is a form of perception, then religious media has not only altered how others perceive blacks, but has also altered how blacks perceive themselves. Televised Redemption argues that black religious media has provided black Americans with new conceptual and practical tools for how to be in the world, and changed how black people are made intelligible and recognizable as moral citizens. In order to make these claims to black racial equality, this media has encouraged dispositional changes in adherents that were at times empowering and at other times repressive. From Christian televangelism to Muslim periodicals to Hebrew Israelite radio, Televised Redemption explores the complicated but critical redemptive history of African American religious media.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aAfrican AmericansxReligion. 0aReligion on television. 0aTelevision broadcastingxReligious aspects. 0aTelevision in religionzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh1 aFrederick, Marla F., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aJackson Jr., John L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831107289890 cprintz978147987603740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479876914423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479876914/original  a978-3-11-072898-9  New York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK